org.itemscript.core.util
Class ChainObject

java.lang.Object
  org.itemscript.core.util.ChainObject
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.util.Map<java.lang.String,JsonValue>, HasSystem, JsonAccess, JsonContainer, JsonObject, JsonValue
public class ChainObject
extends java.lang.Object
implements JsonObject

A pseudo-JsonObject that wraps a list of other JsonObjects. When a value is requested from this ChainObject, it is looked for in each of the objects inside this one in turn; the first object that has a value under that key causes that value to be returned. If none of the objects contains a value under that key, getValue(String) returns null.

All of the JsonObject methods that change the state of the object are not supported; objects of this class also cannot be placed in JsonContainers. Some methods that do not change state are not supported either, although they could be at some point if they were needed.

Author:
Jacob Davies
jacob@itemscript.org

fragment

public java.lang.String fragment()
Description copied from interface: JsonValue
Return the fragment identifier of this value. If this value has no parent container, returns "#". If this value has a parent, but that parent has no parent, returns "#key" where "key" is the value returned by key(), URL-encoded. If this value has a parent, and that parent has a parent, returns "#parent/key", where "#parent" is the fragment identifier of the parent of this value (which may itself be composed of several keys), and "key" is the value returned by key(), URL-encoded.

Specified by:
fragment in interface JsonValue
Returns:
The fragment identifier of this value.

dereference

public final JsonValue dereference(java.lang.String key)
Description copied from interface: JsonAccess
Dereference a value under the given key.

If the value is a JsonString, the string is treated as a URL and retrieved.

If the value is a JsonContainer, the value itself is returned.

If the value is of any other type, an exception will be thrown.

put

public JsonString put(java.lang.String key,
                      byte[] value)
Description copied from interface: JsonAccess
Put a binary value. The value will be base64-encoded and stored in a JsonString.

Note: The JsonString object will point to the underlying byte[] that was supplied; it will not copy it. The internal operations of the JsonSystem will not change it, but it will be made directly available through the JsonString object's JsonValue.binaryValue() method. So, if you need to make sure that the original is not changed, you must copy it before supplying it to this method.

Specified by:
put in interface JsonAccess
Parameters:
key - The key to put the value under.
value - The binary value to store.
Returns:
The new JsonString.

putValue

public JsonValue putValue(java.lang.String key,
                          JsonValue value)
Description copied from interface: JsonAccess
Put a JsonValue.

Note that the return from this method is the value that was returned from the put operation, which differs from the Map.put(K, V) method which returns any previous value that the map had under that key.

Care should be taken when using the JsonObject put method which has the Map put behavior; it is not interchangeable with this putValue method because of the different return values; if you don't care about the return value, there is no difference.

The put methods on JsonSystem and JsonItem are interchangeable with this method.

Specified by:
putValue in interface JsonAccess
Parameters:
key - The key to put the value under.
value - The JsonValue to store.
Returns:
The JsonValue returned by the put operation, which may not be the same value that was given to store.
